{"title":"Tour of Britain favourites and riders to watch","link":"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/tour-of-britain-favourites","date":1693584302000,"content":"<p><a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk\">Cyclist</a><br />\n<a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/tour-of-britain-favourites\">Tour of Britain favourites and riders to watch</a></p>\n\n<p>The <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/tour-of-britain-route-riders-live-tv-guide-all-you-need-to-know\" target=\"_blank\">Tour of Britain</a> starts on Sunday 3rd September and sees plenty of big names take to the start line in Altrincham, Greater Manchester, for eight days of racing in England and Wales. In 2022, the final three stages of the race were cancelled following the death of Queen Elizabeth II; Movistar’s Gonzalo Serrano was declared the winner after Stage 5 and will be back to defend his title.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>But who will be looking to beat him the top step in Caerphilly? Let’s see…</p>\n\n\n<div>\r\n                <div>\r\n                   <div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <h4><span>Related Posts</span></h4>\r\n                      </div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <div>\r\n                            <div>\r\n                            <article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/saint-piran\">State of the nation: Inside the UK domestic racing scene</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/how-to-watch-tour-of-britain\">How to watch and livestream the Tour of Britain 2023</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/tour-of-britain-route-riders-live-tv-guide-all-you-need-to-know\">Tour of Britain 2023: Route, start list and all you need to know</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article></div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <span></span><span></span><span></span>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <div>\r\n                                                <div></div>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <div>\r\n                                                <div></div>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                </div>\r\n                                <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                </div>\r\n                                \r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        </div>\n\n\n<h2>Favourites</h2>\n\n\n\n<h3>Wout van Aert (Jumbo-Visma)</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2022/07/03032932/goding8-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"goding8\" /><figcaption>Pete Goding</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p><a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/tags/wout-van-aert\" target=\"_blank\">Wout van Aert</a> will lead his <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/tags/jumbo-visma\" target=\"_blank\">Jumbo-Visma</a> team and he’ll be looking to repeat his success from 2021, when he won four stages and the general classification. Always a key domestique for teammates in Grand Tours, he’ll get the chance to spread his wings and fly (see above) on the roads of England and Wales. Alongside him will be sprinter Olav Kooij, Edoardo Affini and the ever-present Steven Kruijswijk and Jos van Emden.</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Tom Pidcock (Ineos Grenadiers)</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2022/07/Tom-Pidcock-wins-on-Alpe-dHuez-by-Alex-Broadway-970x647.jpg\" alt srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2022/07/Tom-Pidcock-wins-on-Alpe-dHuez-by-Alex-Broadway-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2022/07/Tom-Pidcock-wins-on-Alpe-dHuez-by-Alex-Broadway-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2022/07/Tom-Pidcock-wins-on-Alpe-dHuez-by-Alex-Broadway-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2022/07/Tom-Pidcock-wins-on-Alpe-dHuez-by-Alex-Broadway-1536x1025.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2022/07/Tom-Pidcock-wins-on-Alpe-dHuez-by-Alex-Broadway-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2022/07/Tom-Pidcock-wins-on-Alpe-dHuez-by-Alex-Broadway-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2022/07/Tom-Pidcock-wins-on-Alpe-dHuez-by-Alex-Broadway-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2022/07/Tom-Pidcock-wins-on-Alpe-dHuez-by-Alex-Broadway-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2022/07/Tom-Pidcock-wins-on-Alpe-dHuez-by-Alex-Broadway-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2022/07/Tom-Pidcock-wins-on-Alpe-dHuez-by-Alex-Broadway.jpg 1832w\" /><figcaption>Alex Broadway/Getty Images</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>One of the most enthralling riders to watch on a bike, <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/tags/tom-pidcock\" target=\"_blank\">Tom Pidcock</a> will once again be racing at the Tour of Britain. He was looking good to challenge Serrano for the title last year before the final stages were cancelled, so expect him to light up the roads in the later part of the race when the route hits the hills. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>Pidcock leads an <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/tags/ineos-grenadiers\" target=\"_blank\">Ineos Grenadiers</a> team that boasts Carlos Rodríguez, Luke Rowe, Magnus Sheffield, Connor Swift and Ben Turner. Sheffield returns to racing for the first time following his crash at the Tour de Suisse in the same spot where Gino Mäder tragically lost his life. </p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Gonzalo Serrano (Movistar)</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2021/09/Gonzalo-Serano-by-Gonzalo-Arroyo-MorenoGetty-Images-970x647.jpg\" alt srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2021/09/Gonzalo-Serano-by-Gonzalo-Arroyo-MorenoGetty-Images-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2021/09/Gonzalo-Serano-by-Gonzalo-Arroyo-MorenoGetty-Images-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2021/09/Gonzalo-Serano-by-Gonzalo-Arroyo-MorenoGetty-Images-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2021/09/Gonzalo-Serano-by-Gonzalo-Arroyo-MorenoGetty-Images-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2021/09/Gonzalo-Serano-by-Gonzalo-Arroyo-MorenoGetty-Images-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2021/09/Gonzalo-Serano-by-Gonzalo-Arroyo-MorenoGetty-Images-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2021/09/Gonzalo-Serano-by-Gonzalo-Arroyo-MorenoGetty-Images-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2021/09/Gonzalo-Serano-by-Gonzalo-Arroyo-MorenoGetty-Images-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2021/09/Gonzalo-Serano-by-Gonzalo-Arroyo-MorenoGetty-Images-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2021/09/Gonzalo-Serano-by-Gonzalo-Arroyo-MorenoGetty-Images.jpg 1701w\" /><figcaption>Gonzalo Arroyo Moreno/Getty Images</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Gonzalo Serrano is back to defend his Tour of Britain title. If successful, the Movistar rider will be the first to do so in the modern era of the race. Serrano recently participated in the road race at the UCI World Championships and opening stage at the Tour of Limousin, DNF’ing both. Alongside him will be Carlos Verona, Fernando Gaviria and Gregor Mühlberger.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Riders to watch</h2>\n\n\n\n<h3>Sam Bennett (Bora-Hansgrohe)</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"683\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2018/01/07095217/tzrm_-_sam_bennett_finish-970x683.jpg\" alt=\"tzrm_-_sam_bennett_finish\" /><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The first part of the Tour of Britain this year is relatively flat, prime for sprinters (or ambitious breakaways) to not only aim for stage wins but sweep up points for the sprint jersey along the route. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>Sam Bennett no doubt has a special place in his heart for the Tour of Britain given that he got his first professional victory here in 2013 in Caerphilly – coincidentally where the 2023 edition finishes. He won two stages and the points classification at the Sibiu Cycling Tour in July and will be lining up alongside Nils Politt, Max Schachmann and Danny van Poppel.</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Stephen Williams (Great Britain)</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"646\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2021/09/Stephen-Williams-wins-Arctic-Race-of-Norway-2023-by-Luc-ClaessenGetty-Images-970x646.jpg\" alt srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2021/09/Stephen-Williams-wins-Arctic-Race-of-Norway-2023-by-Luc-ClaessenGetty-Images-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2021/09/Stephen-Williams-wins-Arctic-Race-of-Norway-2023-by-Luc-ClaessenGetty-Images-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2021/09/Stephen-Williams-wins-Arctic-Race-of-Norway-2023-by-Luc-ClaessenGetty-Images-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2021/09/Stephen-Williams-wins-Arctic-Race-of-Norway-2023-by-Luc-ClaessenGetty-Images-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2021/09/Stephen-Williams-wins-Arctic-Race-of-Norway-2023-by-Luc-ClaessenGetty-Images-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2021/09/Stephen-Williams-wins-Arctic-Race-of-Norway-2023-by-Luc-ClaessenGetty-Images-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2021/09/Stephen-Williams-wins-Arctic-Race-of-Norway-2023-by-Luc-ClaessenGetty-Images-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2021/09/Stephen-Williams-wins-Arctic-Race-of-Norway-2023-by-Luc-ClaessenGetty-Images-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2021/09/Stephen-Williams-wins-Arctic-Race-of-Norway-2023-by-Luc-ClaessenGetty-Images-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2021/09/Stephen-Williams-wins-Arctic-Race-of-Norway-2023-by-Luc-ClaessenGetty-Images.jpg 1772w\" /><figcaption>Luc Claessen/Getty Images</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Riding for the Great Britain team (not his trade team <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/tags/israel-premier-tech\" target=\"_blank\">Israel-Premier Tech</a>), Stevie Williams will be alongside a squad of talent including Track Elimination World Champion Ethan Vernon and Circuit Race National Champion Oliver Wood. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>Williams was at the Arctic Race of Norway last month and stormed to victory on the third stage up to Havøysund ahead of Clément Champoussin (Arkéa-Samsic) and Christian Scaroni (Astana Qazaqstan). He won the overall classification by one second, taking home a pretty snazzy trophy and a yellow jersey.</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Harry Tanfield (TdT-Unibet)</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"646\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2019/10/07095220/harry_tanfield_qa_1-970x646.jpg\" alt=\"harry_tanfield_qa_1\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2019/10/07095220/harry_tanfield_qa_1-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2019/10/07095220/harry_tanfield_qa_1-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2019/10/07095220/harry_tanfield_qa_1-768x511.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2019/10/07095220/harry_tanfield_qa_1-1536x1022.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2019/10/07095220/harry_tanfield_qa_1-750x499.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2019/10/07095220/harry_tanfield_qa_1-1140x759.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2019/10/07095220/harry_tanfield_qa_1-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2019/10/07095220/harry_tanfield_qa_1-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2019/10/07095220/harry_tanfield_qa_1.jpg 2000w\" /><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Continental teams and the Tour of Britain: a story for the ages. From Jacob Scott from Canyon-Dhb-SunGod winning the mountains, sprints and combativity award in 2021 (and the mountains classification with SwiftCarbon Pro Cycling in 2019) to Rory Townsend and Alex Paton (both Canyon-Dhb-SunGod but under different names – there’s a theme here) both winning the sprint classifications, the domestic teams always seem to light up the race.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Harry Tanfield, who won Heusden Koers last month, has switched between Continental and WorldTour level over the years, from Canyon-Eisberg to Katusha-Alpecin, AG2R-La Mondiale to Qhubeka NextHash, Ribble-Weldtite Pro Cycling and now over to TdT-Unibet in the Netherlands. Keep an eye on 28-year-old Tanfield to potentially jump in a breakaway or two.</p>\n<p>The post <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/tour-of-britain-favourites\">Tour of Britain favourites and riders to watch</a> appeared first on <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk\">Cyclist</a>.</p>","author":"jrobinson","siteTitle":"Cyclist.co.uk","siteHash":"561486e7070fa5351de9318ad0fa26c2a39332acba5fc7c7d1694a01d53d431e","entryHash":"aa83287560f8d0700601460aa569fac64370d422ca0fc7d8fcd0b4561b27814a","category":"Cycling"}